defaultEngineering measuresdefaultLondon TravelWatch strongly favours data-led interventions on London’s streets. The clamour for ‘cycling
default infrastructure’ may well lead to poorly targeted schemes that do not take into account all users and do not properly allocate limited resources where they will be most effective. For example the cycle superhighway between Stratford and the Bow roundabout 
defaultjunction along Stratford High Street has resulted in the loss of a bus priority lane for London’s busiest bus
default, route 
default25.
default 
defaultThere are also proposals, as part of this 
defaultscheme, that
default in the name of cycle safety, introduce cyclists onto the pavement and introduce 
defaultadditional kerbs. Pedestrians, particularly elderly, and mobility and visually impaired users want level and continuous pavements, not kerbs
default. They
default 
defaultdislike
default cycling on the pavement, because of the actual and perceived safety risks that cyclists pose for them
default.
defaultMost casualties occur at busy road junctions. For this reason road safety specialists have historically focussed their efforts at these locations. London TravelWatch 
defaultbelieves this should continue and particularly welcomes 
defaultTfL’s  junctions’
default review which t
defaultargets those locations with a history of collisions. 
defaultHowever, there are conflicting policies for London’s streets. There is policy to maintain and enhance motor vehicle capacity whilst at the same time a policy to re-model junctions to be safer for cyclin
defaultg. It is difficult to see how
default, in any practical sense,
default these conflicts can be resolved without the more widespread implementation of roads pricing to reduce vehicle volumes. 
defaultLondon TravelWatch considers that there is much scope to improve the safety of cy
defaultclists on London’s streets through a variety of engineering changes that minimise any detrimental impact on other users such as:
